@page "/button"
<PageTitle>Button - Saascade Docs</PageTitle>

<h1 id="button-component">Button</h1>

<div class="doc-layout">

<main class="documentation">

    <TechCard>
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>

            <p class="subtitle">
                The Button component renders a standard HTML button element with design-system-aware class names.
                Use the framework filter to see how the Button behaves in each supported design system.
            </p>

            <hr />

            <p>
                The component accepts optional specialization classes, inline styles, a tooltip, and any child content.
                The actual CSS classes applied depend on the active design system registered in your application.
            </p>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

    <TechCard>
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="parameters">Parameters</h2>

            <table>
                <thead>
                    <tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Type</th><th>Description</th></tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr><td>Class</td><td>string?</td><td>Additional CSS classes.</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>Specialization</td><td>string?</td><td>Design system variant classes.</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>Style</td><td>string?</td><td>Inline styles.</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>Tooltip</td><td>string?</td><td>Tooltip text.</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>ChildContent</td><td>RenderFragment</td><td>Button label or content.</td></tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

    <TechCard Tech="bootstrap">
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="bootstrap-button">Bootstrap 5 Button</h2>

            <p class="subtitle">
                In Bootstrap 5, the Button component maps to the btn class. Variants such as btn-primary,
                btn-secondary, or btn-outline-danger are applied via the Specialization parameter.
            </p>

            <hr />

            <p>
                Bootstrap 5 buttons follow the standard btn base class model. The design system resolves
                the correct class prefix and the Specialization value is appended to produce the full class
                string. A primary action button renders as a solid filled button, while outline variants
                produce a bordered style with a transparent background.
            </p>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

    <TechCard Tech="daisyui">
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="daisyui-button">DaisyUI Button</h2>

            <p class="subtitle">
                In DaisyUI, the Button component maps to the btn class with Tailwind-based semantic
                variants such as btn-primary, btn-ghost, or btn-outline.
            </p>

            <hr />

            <p>
                DaisyUI buttons are built on Tailwind CSS and use semantic color tokens tied to your
                theme configuration. The Specialization parameter accepts any valid DaisyUI button
                modifier. Because DaisyUI is theme-aware, switching between light and dark themes
                updates button colors automatically without changing markup.
            </p>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

    <TechCard Tech="basecoat">
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="basecoat-button">Basecoat Button</h2>

            <p class="subtitle">
                In Basecoat, the Button component uses utility-first Tailwind classes to produce
                a minimal, unstyled-by-default button that you can compose freely.
            </p>

            <hr />

            <p>
                Basecoat buttons are composed from low-level Tailwind utilities rather than opinionated
                component classes. The design system provides a sensible default set of utility classes
                for layout and focus states. The Specialization parameter appends additional utilities,
                giving you fine-grained control over padding, color, border-radius, and interaction styles.
            </p>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

</main>

<TableOfContents Items="@([
    new TocItem("button-component", "Button"),
    new TocItem("overview", "Overview", 2),
    new TocItem("parameters", "Parameters", 2),
    new TocItem("bootstrap-button", "Bootstrap 5 Button", 2, "bootstrap"),
    new TocItem("daisyui-button", "DaisyUI Button", 2, "daisyui"),
    new TocItem("basecoat-button", "Basecoat Button", 2, "basecoat")
])" />

</div>
